So many masks were made by our community for Newportâ€™s students. It was incredible! We still have LOTS of fabric leftover. If your student would like a mask with a particular pattern/color, Jenna Darling is willing to make some additional masks (at no charge).

Introducing Katie Haynes, Grade 5 Richards Elementary

Katie joined Richards last February as part of the third grade team and will be working as a fifth grade teacher for the 2020-2021 school year. She has a strong background in project-based-learning and is thrilled to bring her experience to Richards. Katie taught environment education at NH Audubon summer camps, which brought together her love of nature and teaching. Katie is looking forward to finding innovative ways to extend learning outside of the classroom through projects and time spent outdoors.

post_text:
This year we have 15 new teachers to Tiger Nation. Please help us welcome them as we kick off the new year! Each day we will highlight one of the newest members! Today, meet Allison Howe.

Hi! My name is Allison Howe. I will be teaching third grade at Richards Elementary School this fall. I am a Newport native who is very familiar with town traditions and the beauty of this community. I graduated from Plymouth State University in December 2019 with my Bachelor's in Elementary Education grades K-8. Although this will be my very first year teaching, I come to the Newport School District having worked with students of all grade levels across the state through substitute teaching and practicum experiences. On a more personal level, I love to go to the beach, hike, and hang out with friends and family. My favorite season is fall and I love everything pumpkin and apple flavored. Also, like many other teachers, I run on coffee. I cannot wait to start the 2020-2021 school year and get to know many of the students at Richards!
text:
This year we have 15 new teachers to Tiger Nation. Please help us welcome them as we kick off the new year! Each day we will highlight one of the newest members! Today, meet Allison Howe.

Hi! My name is Allison Howe. I will be teaching third grade at Richards Elementary School this fall. I am a Newport native who is very familiar with town traditions and the beauty of this community. I graduated from Plymouth State University in December 2019 with my Bachelor's in Elementary Education grades K-8. Although this will be my very first year teaching, I come to the Newport School District having worked with students of all grade levels across the state through substitute teaching and practicum experiences. On a more personal level, I love to go to the beach, hike, and hang out with friends and family. My favorite season is fall and I love everything pumpkin and apple flavored. Also, like many other teachers, I run on coffee. I cannot wait to start the 2020-2021 school year and get to know many of the students at Richards!

post_text:
On Saturday, August 8 at 10 AM we will be celebrating the retirement of three beloved Newport teachers. While we were in quarantine, Steve Christensen, Newport teacher for 15 years, Stephanie Gilson, 37 years and Barbara Kvetcovsky, 57 years! quietly retired.

We can't give them the celebration they deserve, but we can give them a fantastic farewell parade. I know they will love to see colleagues, former students and friends. Please swing on by and feel free to make signs and decorate your car. We will also have a basket to collect cards and notes. Hope to see you there.

We will line up at the Newport Rec Center and proceed down Meadow Street past the Pavilion at the park and then on out to South Main Street.

Let's show them all how much we appreciate their dedication to Newport's students.

Hey Class of 2021! Unsure of what your future plans might be? Do they possibly involve continuing your education? If you are considering applying to college, please make sure you take the SAT because we did not have our school day SAT this year.

SAT registration is now open and we recommend signing up as soon as possible. The College Board is predicting high demand and limited availability for test dates and seats, and we want to make sure you are all able to take the SAT if you want or need to.

The College Board plans to offer a Fall SAT in replacement of the Spring School day SAT that was cancelled, but at this time, we have no specific information regarding that.

Please go to collegeboard.org/sat to find test dates and registration information. If you have any questions or would like information regarding fee waivers, please contact Hayley Sharp at hsharp@sau43.org.

post_text:
Updated graduation information (in particular, see those updated items highlighted in yellow).

Also:

There will be a senior prom parade this Saturday, June 6 at 2:00 PM. Seniors will have opportunities to take pictures from 12:30-1:30 PM at the opera house, town common, and Corbin Covered Bridge.

Seniors will meet at the high school at 1:45 PM, entering through Thurlow Drive, to line up and begin the parade at 2:00 PM. The route will begin at the high school, proceed through the center of town, taking a right at the intersection, up Elm Street, onto Pine Street, down Belknap Avenue and return back to the high school.

Seniors may wear prom attire, dress attire, casual attire, or caps and gowns.

Students may ride in a vehicle with members of their household or they may ride with a date not from their household. Students who are not from the same household but in the same vehicle must wear a mask while in the car together.

Please remember to wear masks and practice social distancing during this event.

post_text:
The Newport School District is looking for a few parent and community volunteers to help us plan for whatever the fall school year brings. There will be three different working groups composed of school and district employees, school board members, parents/guardians, and members of the community. The plan is to have each group hold about three to four meetings remotely during the month of June to create draft documents to inform our planning.

The three working groups are planning for the following scenarios in the fall:

1. Remote learning only
2. Hybrid model with both in-person and remote learning
3. Traditional model of in-person learning

If you are interested in serving on one of these work groups, please send an email to bminnihan@sau43.org by Friday, May 22nd.

Be well.

Brendan Minnihan

On Saturday, April 9, the Class of 2021 held a Clean Up Day out behind Dollar General. In two hours they filled ninety-two trash bags.

There were many other things such as a box spring, old tires, a shopping cart and other large items that were thrown into the truck to be hauled away.

The class would like to thank PJ Lovely for organizing this event. Thank you to Mr. West for the truck and taking everything to the dump. Thank you to the parents who showed up to help as well. They would also like to thank everyone who sponsored this event.

Richards Student Belongings Pickup Schedule:

We will be doing a drive thru style pickup of student belongings at the Towle Gym on Wednesday 5/13. We will be doing three shifts to allow as many opportunities to accommodate as possible. The first shift will be 9:00am to 11:00am, the second will be 1:00pm to 3:00pm, and the third will be 5:00pm to 7:00pm. Please drive through the parking lot at the town library and out to Belknap Ave. You will remain in your vehicle and tell the waiting staff who your child is and their bag will be brought out to you. We will also have the Lost & Found items from Richards set up along the fence outside so you may look through to see if anything belongs to your child. Items not picked up will be delivered with student work over the following week. Please email if you have any questions: jpackard@sau43.org.

A few copies left!

Free - 11" X 17" 21 page coloring story book about the Corbin Covered Bridge by Sharon Christie, compliments of the Newport Historical Society.

Sharon Christie was executive assistant to the town manager during the Corbin Covered Bridge rebuilding effort and played a large role. She and others on the Festival Committee worked tirelessly for the â€œhomecomingâ€ of the Corbin Covered Bridge in 1994. Her town report featuring Newportâ€™s covered bridges published that year won two awards.

Sharonâ€™s passion for the community of Newport resonates today and it is through the generous donations of the families and friends you see mentioned on each page that we are able to share this story and Sharonâ€™s love for the Corbin Covered Bridge for all generations in a multi-purpose format to read, color and share.

Sharon Christie was executive assistant to the town manager during the Corbin Covered Bridge rebuilding effort and played a large role. She and others on the Festival Committee worked tirelessly for the â€œhomecomingâ€ of the Corbin Covered Bridge in 1994. Her town report featuring Newportâ€™s covered bridges published that year won two awards.

Sharonâ€™s passion for the community of Newport resonates today and it is through the generous donations of the families and friends you see mentioned on each page that we are able to share this story and Sharonâ€™s love for the Corbin Covered Bridge for all generations in a multi-purpose format to read, color and share.

MCC Hosting a Virtual Open House
Hi! Manchester Community College will be hosting a Virtual Open House this coming Wednesday, May 6th from 4:00-6:00pm. Students can visit our homepage at www.mccnh.edu to join the Open House virtually using Zoom.
Students will have the ability to visit the different programs and departments, including financial aid and our disability services, to ask their questions and find out more information about MCC! As always, admissions will be available to help them through the application process. We're an open enrollment college, so there's still plenty of time for students to apply and get registered for the Summer and Fall Semesters!
Please let your students know!
Stay healthy and we hope to see you all soon!

The Admissions Team

(603) 206-8000 | www.mccnh.edu

post_text:
Want help making plans for your future? Need help making a resume? Want help searching colleges that are right for you?

Check out SCOIR!

SCOIR (pronounced score) takes into account YOUR interests and shows you what colleges meet the needs you are looking for. You can even compare and contrast up to 4 schools at once, and get reviews from current students at those colleges. (Hey Parents! In the parent view, there is also a net price calculator that gives you an estimate of how much each school would cost!) Check out the video below for more information on what SCOIR has to offer!

To start using SCOIR, check your school email! You will have an email invite from SCOIR. Just follow the directions and start filling out your profile! A few first steps you should take are to invite a parent, fill out your activities and achievements, and college preferences! Then start your searching! *If you do not use the invitation within 72 hours, just email your counselor for a new link!

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NKyaNX5Dqq4&t=4s

Got questions? Contact your school counselor!

post_text:
Third quarter report cards are available on PowerSchool. Please see the instructions below for how to access your child/children's report card.

1. Log into your Parent Portal account with PowerSchool.

2. On the left hand side, click on the Report Cards" icon.

3. You will see a list of archived report cards with Quarter 3 listed at the top. Click to open.

If you do not remember your password to the parent portal or you do not have a PowerSchool account, please use the Help Desk Ticket to request access.

If you are unable to access the internet to view your student's report card and require a paper copy, please contact the SAU at 865-9500.

Miss Morrison and Mrs. Benoit just wrapped up the first week of their â€œSpirit Week Read Aloudâ€ and thought they would share some pictures with you.
Miss Morrison and Mrs. Benoit have been taking turns reading chapters of a book to their students. They also had an activity or challenge to do each day that goes along with the read aloud chapter. Some of the activities included: wear a striped shirt like a pirate, wear sunglasses and flip flops, make your own treasure map and secret code, and take a picture of you and your pet! They are continuing with another spirit week this week as well!

post_text:
NMHS school nurse, Kassy Helie, writes:

I had the privilege of working Monday at the Got Lunch Food Program. Charen Urban, longtime teacher at NHS, is spearheading it. This is a different program than the one the district is doing for our students today. It was developed so that families could receive food over the summer. This week deliveries were made to 52 families, feeding 126 students. She anticipates that this number is going to go up.

The next delivery date is going to be April 6. Charen goes to our food pantry and the state food bank, but also has funds available to shop locally. The program is always looking for donations. All the bags are the same so donations are better when they are specific.

For the April 6 delivery she is looking for bottles of jelly, small cans of tuna or chicken and jars of mayonnaise. There will be a dropbox near the front door at the SAU office in Towle if you're able to help.
text:
NMHS school nurse, Kassy Helie, writes:

I had the privilege of working Monday at the Got Lunch Food Program. Charen Urban, longtime teacher at NHS, is spearheading it. This is a different program than the one the district is doing for our students today. It was developed so that families could receive food over the summer. This week deliveries were made to 52 families, feeding 126 students. She anticipates that this number is going to go up.

The next delivery date is going to be April 6. Charen goes to our food pantry and the state food bank, but also has funds available to shop locally. The program is always looking for donations. All the bags are the same so donations are better when they are specific.

For the April 6 delivery she is looking for bottles of jelly, small cans of tuna or chicken and jars of mayonnaise. There will be a dropbox near the front door at the SAU office in Towle if you're able to help.

Message to NMHS band students from Ms. Emma Nelson:

During this transition time it is crucial that students have their instruments at home with them to practice and stay up to date with assignments through google classroom.

Ms. Nelson will be at the school tomorrow (Tuesday 3/17) from 9:00 am to 2:00 pm so that students or their guardians can pick up their instruments and music. THIS INCLUDES GUITAR STUDENTS.

Also at this time, within the next week we will be transitioning to the new band director, Mr. Carey Citak. He will be assigning work through google classroom and keeping in communication with students so that they can continue to learn. If you have any questions for him, please feel free to reach out to him through email (ccitak@sau43.org).

Thank you so much for your flexibility and understanding during the last few weeks and the weeks to come. Stay healthy.

post_text:
Good Morning Tiger Nation,

This morning we received notification that a staff member who has minimal contact with students is currently being tested for the COVID-19 (Coronavirus) illness. Out of an abundance of caution, we will be doing an early release today to allow us time to monitor the situation and deep clean the buildings.

Newport Middle High School will be dismissing today, March 12th at 11:30am and Richards Elementary School will be dismissing at 12:30pm with no PM preschool. All afternoon activities have been canceled for today.

Additionally, the lockdown drill at the middle/high school today is unrelated to this incident and was part of our regularly scheduled drills.

Thank you for help and understanding as we navigate this dismissal. It is important to remember this is precautionary in nature and what we believe in the best interest of our students. As we are able, we will provide an update with more information.

Thank you,
Newport School District

Newport school and community apparel is here! The business program has been working on a year-long project to design and implement a much-needed new line of clothing for our entire school and community. Right now we are offering t-shirts for $15, long-sleeved shirts for $20 and sweatshirts for $30 that are available in the school store.

We have two different designs and offer different color options as well. We accept cash and checks made out to SRVRTC. Flyers were given to your studentâ€™s advisor and should have gone home this weekend. We will be expanding our line in the near future and a new school store website is in the works.

Any questions, please email Jaime LeFlem, jleflem@sau43.org.

post_text:
The month of February is Teen Dating Violence Awareness Month. One in three young people will be in abusive or unhealthy relationships. Only a third of those teens involved in abusive relationships confide in someone about the violence.

This week specifically is Granite State RESPECT Week. RESPECT Week aims to promote healthy relationships and prevent teen dating violence in schools across New Hampshire.

On Friday, Life of a Tiger will be in the main lobby during WIN sharing characteristics of healthy and unhealthy relationships and other resources. High school students, stop by the lobby and share with us what you think it means to be in a healthy relationship and win a prize!

post_text:
The Newport indoor track team had a great day at the Division II state meet today at Dartmouth College.

The Tigers finished seventh out of 24 scoring teams with 16 points.

Mason Martell led Newport with a second place finish in the 55 meter hurdles in a record time of 7.86 seconds and has qualified for the New England Meet at the Reggie Lewis Center in Boston on Feb. 29.

The 4x200 meter relay team of Darshawn Chesser, Jagger Lovely, Ryder Lovely and Martell also had a big day finishing third in a school record time of 1:36.02. The Tiger quartet also qualified for the New Englands.

Jagger Lovely rounded out the scoring for the Tigers with a fifth place finish in the 55 meters.

Oyster River won the meet followed by Windham and Coe-Brown

post_text:
Congratulations to the unified basketball team coached by Chelsea Belinsky and Lisa Gilson for their win over Fall Mountain 48-33 Wednesday afternoon.

The win ended a 31-game winning streak for the Fall Mountain team which had never lost a unified game before yesterday.

A shout-out to players Max Wadensten, Abby Carley, Madison Aldrich, Jasmyn Wilkinson, Ethan Trombley, Bridget Livingstone and helpers Riely Skarin, Maddie Miller, Greysan Beaulieu, Eliza Bates and Morgan Roberts.

Senior parents & guardians: We will meet this Sunday, January 12 at 6:30 at the high school in Mrs. Mitchler's classroom.

At this meeting we will distribute donation collection letters for you to bring to businesses to help solicit donations needed for substance-free. If you have volunteered to reach out to a business, please plan to attend.

We will work hard in January and February to gather as many donations as possible so our next meeting will be in March.

I look forward to seeing you all Sunday night!

Christy Whipple
603-477-9014
misschristy@newportmontessori.org

post_text:
The Newport indoor track team had a great day at Dartmouth this past weekend. The boys finished fourth behind Thetford (third), Keene (second) and Nashua North (first).

Jagger Lovely led the way with a second in the 55-meter dash with a school record of 6.81, and a third place in the 300-meter with a school record run of 37.62. Ryder Lovely posted a school record third place in the 600 at 1:34.73.

The boysâ€™ 4 x 200 meter relay team also garnered a second place, with freshman Darren Janicke anchoring the team of Darshawn Chesser, Ryder Lovely and Jagger Lovely with a time of 1:39.73. Freshman Tim Fratzel and eighth-grader Brooke Johnson posted solid times in their first Indoor meet.

The team competes again this coming Sunday at Dartmouth.

Newport School Board Hiring Committee Begins Application Review

The Newport School Board superintendent search committee met on Monday, December 9 from 5:00 - 8:00 pm in the Sugar River Valley Regional Technology Center to begin reviewing the twelve applications submitted for the superintendentâ€™s position starting July 1, 2020. The district is currently administered by interim superintendent, Dr. Brendan Minnihan.

Before beginning review of the applications, the search committee practiced using the criteria for applicant evaluation determined through community surveys and discussion over several hours of meetings held in the last three months.

The next meeting is planned for Tuesday, December 17 at 5:00 pm. Because this meeting will involve the hiring of a person as a public employee, the meeting is posted as non-public meeting under RSA-91:A 3, II(b).

post_text:
NHS' Life of a Tiger will be putting on a toy drive the week of December 16. Each advisory will be competing to collect the most toys. Students should bring toys to their advisor and at the end of the week, the advisory with the most toys collected will win a breakfast and baked goods party.

This toy drive will benefit the Toys for Tots organization. Toys that will be accepted are those suitable for children up to age 12, such as board games, sporting equipment, books, cosmetics, etc.

Toys for Tots will not accept realistic looking toy weapons, such as nerf guns and swords, and gifts with food.

If you have any questions please see Morgan Roberts, Hayley Avery, or Ms. Porter. Thanks!

post_text:
The Newport School Board superintendent search committee met on Monday, October 28 to draft the job posting for the upcoming superintendent's position to be hired for the upcoming school year. The job description was formed using the information gathered in the community survey and competency criteria created by the committee. The posting will be distributed locally and nationally. Plans are to post immediately with a November 22 application deadline.

Currently leading the district is interim superintendent, Dr. Brendan Minnihan. â€œWe are extremely pleased with the job Brendan is doing,â€ states board member, Ann Spencer. â€œDr. Minnihan accepted the superintendency as a one-year interim, which has different priorities than the permanent position. That said, he is in an ideal position to decide if this job would be a good fit for him, in which case he is - like any other candidate - encouraged to apply.â€

The committee next meets on Sunday, November 24 to begin to evaluate the applications.

The Richards School math carnival is Tuesday, October 22 from 5:00 to 6:30 p.m. It is free to all Richards students. Students do math activities and games to earn "carnival cash". They then can spend their carnival cash on carnival games or in a variety of other ways like a wagon ride, tattoo, make a craft, and pumpkin raffle to name a few.
